Constructed in the early 4th century, the tumulus underwent alterations in later periods. Excavations by Fukuoka City revealed traces of {{ill|fukiishi|ja|葺石|12=draft}}, enabling estimates of its original area. burial goods recovered from the site include fragments of {{ill|beast-motif mirrors|ja|獣帯鏡|12=draft}} and {{ill|haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft}}, suggesting that this tumulus is among the oldest burial sites of regional chieftains in the Imajuku Plain.

