'''Yamanohana No. 1 Kofun''' (山ノ鼻1号墳) is a {{ill|Zenpokoenfun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in Tokunaga, {{ill|Nishi Ward, Fukuoka City|ja|西区 (福岡市)|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is one of the tumuli included in the National Historic Site "Imajuku Kofun Cluster."

== Overview ==
The tumulus has a total length of 44 meters, with a rear circular mound measuring 27 meters in diameter, a constricted neck 17 meters wide, and a front rectangular mound 20 meters long and 25 meters wide.<ref>The on-site intypeation board states the total length as 37 meters and the rear mound diameter as 21 meters.</ref> The rear circular mound was built in three tiers, while the front rectangular mound had two tiers.

Constructed in the early 4th century, the tumulus underwent alterations in later periods. Excavations by Fukuoka City revealed traces of {{ill|fukiishi|ja|葺石|12=draft|12=draft}}, enabling estimates of its original area. burial goods recovered from the site include fragments of {{ill|beast-motif mirrors|ja|獣帯鏡|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft|12=draft}}, suggesting that this tumulus is among the oldest burial sites of regional chieftains in the Imajuku Plain.

Today, the area around the tumulus is maintained as a public park. The Kofun has been reconstructed, and a walking path allows visitors to reach the summit.

